          <h2>Getting Here</h2>
          <p>Newark is well connected by road and rail, making it easy to reach from across the country.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid grid--3">
          <div class="info-card">
            <h3>
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><rect x="1" y="3" width="15" height="13"/><polygon points="16 8 20 8 23 11 23 16 16 16 16 8"/><circle cx="5.5" cy="18.5" r="2.5"/><circle cx="18.5" cy="18.5" r="2.5"/></svg>
              By Train
            </h3>
            <p>Newark has two railway stations:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Newark North Gate</strong> — on the East Coast Main Line (LNER, Grand Central). Direct services from London King's Cross in approximately 1 hour 20 minutes. Also served by trains to/from Edinburgh, York, Leeds, and Peterborough.</li>
              <li><strong>Newark Castle</strong> — on the Nottingham to Lincoln line (East Midlands Railway). Convenient for reaching Newark from Nottingham (~25 mins) and Lincoln (~20 mins).</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="info-card">
            <h3>
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M14 16H9m10 0h3v-3.15a1 1 0 0 0-.84-.99L16 11l-2.7-3.6a1 1 0 0 0-.8-.4H5.24a2 2 0 0 0-1.8 1.1l-.8 1.63A6 6 0 0 0 2 12.42V16h2"/><circle cx="6.5" cy="16.5" r="2.5"/><circle cx="16.5" cy="16.5" r="2.5"/></svg>
              By Car
            </h3>
            <p>Newark sits at a junction of major routes:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>A1</strong> — the Great North Road runs just east of the town, providing fast access from London (approx. 2.5 hours) and the north.</li>
              <li><strong>A46</strong> — connecting Newark to Leicester and the M1 to the south-west, and Lincoln to the north-east.</li>
              <li><strong>A17</strong> — links Newark to Sleaford and the Lincolnshire coast.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>East Midlands Airport is around an hour's drive away.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="info-card">
            <h3>
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M8 6v6"/><path d="M15 6v6"/><path d="M2 12h19.6"/><path d="M18 18h3s.5-1.7.8-2.8c.1-.4.2-.8.2-1.2 0-.4-.1-.8-.2-1.2l-1.4-5C20.1 6.8 19.1 6 18 6H4a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v10h3"/><circle cx="7" cy="18" r="2"/><path d="M9 18h5"/><circle cx="16" cy="18" r="2"/></svg>
              By Bus
            </h3>
            <p>Regular bus services connect Newark to surrounding towns and cities:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Services to and from Nottingham, Lincoln, Grantham, and Sleaford</li>
              <li>The bus station is centrally located on Lombard Street, a short walk from the Market Square</li>
              <li>Stagecoach and other operators run frequent services throughout the day</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
